        <a name="why-rampant"></a>
        <div class="section-block" id="why-rampant">
          <h2>Why African Grey Parrot Scams Are Rampant in 2025–2026</h2>

          <div class="snippet-answer">
            <strong>African Grey parrot scams are surging in 2025–2026</strong> because these birds are one of the most in-demand, highest-value pet species in the world — yet legitimate, CITES-documented captive-bred birds are genuinely difficult to find. Scammers exploit the gap between high demand and limited supply, using stolen photos, fake websites, and advance-fee fraud to steal $200–$2,000+ from buyers before the "bird" ever ships.
          </div>

          <p>The African Grey parrot (<em>Psittacus erithacus</em>) is listed under <strong>CITES Appendix I</strong> — a protected species whose international trade is strictly regulated. Wild-caught African Greys have been banned from import to the United States since 1992 under the Wild Bird Conservation Act. Every legitimate African Grey for sale in the U.S. must be <strong>captive-bred</strong> — <a href="/captive-bred-african-grey-parrot/">our captive-bred guide explains exactly what that status guarantees</a> — documented with CITES papers, and sold by a <strong>USDA AWA licensed facility</strong>.</p>

          <p>Scammers know most buyers don't understand these requirements. They post fake listings on Facebook Marketplace, Craigslist, Hoobly, and Kijiji — offering birds that don't exist at prices far below market rate. By the time a buyer realizes they've been defrauded, the scammer has vanished with the deposit.</p>

