        <!-- ===== SECTION 8: VERIFY CITES ===== -->
        <a name="verify-cites"></a>
        <div class="section-block" id="verify-cites">
          <h2>How to Verify CITES Documentation for an African Grey Parrot</h2>

          <p>CITES (Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species) Appendix I documentation is the legal proof that your African Grey parrot was captive-bred — not wild-caught. African Greys were uplisted from Appendix II to <strong>Appendix I at CoP17, effective January 2017</strong>, which is exactly why scammers now wave fake "CITES certificates" at buyers who know the term but not the paperwork. Here at C.A.Gs we hand every buyer the real thing, and <a href="/cites-african-grey-documentation/">our complete CITES documentation guide</a> walks through each form line by line. Below is what real CITES documentation looks like and how to verify it.</p>

          <!-- Infographic: CITES documentation example -->
          <figure class="ig-panel" aria-label="What Real CITES Appendix I Documentation Must Include">
            <div class="ig-head">
              <span class="ig-eyebrow">Documentation Checklist</span>
              <span class="ig-title">What Real CITES Appendix I Documentation Must Include</span>
            </div>
            <div class="ig-body ig-cols-2">
              <div class="ig-check">
                <span class="mk">✓</span>
                <div><strong>Species &amp; Scientific Name</strong><span>Psittacus erithacus — must appear in full</span></div>
              </div>
              <div class="ig-check">
                <span class="mk">✓</span>
                <div><strong>Issuing Authority Signature</strong><span>USFWS or equivalent government body</span></div>
              </div>
              <div class="ig-check">
                <span class="mk">✓</span>
                <div><strong>Captive-Bred Declaration</strong><span>Must state "born in captivity" explicitly</span></div>
              </div>
              <div class="ig-check">
                <span class="mk">✓</span>
                <div><strong>Breeder Facility Information</strong><span>Name, address, USDA AWA license number</span></div>
              </div>
              <div class="ig-check">
                <span class="mk">✓</span>
                <div><strong>Hatch Certificate &amp; Band Number</strong><span>Unique ID linking bird to documentation</span></div>
              </div>
              <div class="ig-check bad">
                <span class="mk">✗</span>
                <div><strong>No Documents = Red Flag</strong><span>Any seller who can't provide this is either selling illegally or running a scam</span></div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </figure>

          <h3>What CITES Documentation Must Include</h3>
          <h4 class="qa-label">Can I Buy an African Grey Without CITES Documentation?</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Species designation:</strong> <em>Psittacus erithacus</em> (Congo) or <em>Psittacus timneh</em> (Timneh) — the full scientific name</li>
            <li><strong>"Captive-bred" declaration:</strong> Explicitly stating the bird was bred in captivity, not wild-caught</li>
            <li><strong>Hatch date and band/ring number:</strong> The bird's individual identification — must match the physical band on the bird's leg</li>
            <li><strong>Breeder facility name and USDA AWA license number</strong></li>
            <li><strong>Issuing authority signature:</strong> Signed by a USDA-authorized official or CITES authority</li>
            <li><strong>Date of issue</strong> — documentation should be issued at the time of the bird's sale</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>How to Verify CITES Documentation Is Real</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Request the documentation in writing (email or PDF) <strong>before sending any payment</strong></li>
            <li>Cross-reference the USDA AWA license number in the document against the USDA public database</li>
            <li>Confirm the band number on the document matches the physical leg band visible in video call</li>
            <li>Check that the issuing authority is a real, verifiable USDA-registered entity</li>
            <li>Contact USDA APHIS directly at (844) 820-2234 if you have doubts about document authenticity</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="snippet-answer">
            <strong>Quick check:</strong> Ask the breeder — <em>"Can you email me the CITES Appendix I captive-bred certificate before we proceed?"</em> A legitimate breeder responds with the document within hours. A scammer deflects: "We send documentation after payment," "The CITES papers are prepared by our vet," or "We don't handle that paperwork directly." Any deflection is a disqualifying red flag.
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- ===== SECTION 9: REVERSE IMAGE SEARCH ===== -->
        <a name="reverse-image"></a>
        <div class="section-block" id="reverse-image">
          <h2>How to Reverse Image Search a Bird Photo (30-Second Scam Check)</h2>

          <p>The fastest scam detection tool available to any buyer is a reverse image search. It takes 30 seconds and has exposed more African Grey parrot scams than any other single technique.</p>

          <!-- Infographic: Reverse image search walkthrough -->
          <figure class="ig-panel" aria-label="How to Reverse Image Search a Parrot Photo — 3 Steps">
            <div class="ig-head">
              <span class="ig-eyebrow">Catch Stolen Photos Instantly</span>
              <span class="ig-title">Reverse Image Search in 30 Seconds</span>
            </div>
            <div class="ig-body ig-steps">
              <div class="ig-step">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="1.7em" height="1.7em" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.9" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M3 3l7.07 16.97 2.51-7.39 7.39-2.51z"/><path d="m13 13 6 6"/></svg>
                <span class="lbl">Step 1</span>
                <strong>Right-Click the Photo</strong>
                <span>Select "Search image with Google" in Chrome/Edge</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ig-arrow">→</div>
              <div class="ig-step">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="1.7em" height="1.7em" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.9" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><circle cx="11" cy="11" r="8"/><line x1="21" y1="21" x2="16.65" y2="16.65"/></svg>
                <span class="lbl">Step 2</span>
                <strong>Or Upload to TinEye</strong>
                <span>tineye.com or images.google.com if right-click blocked</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ig-arrow">→</div>
              <div class="ig-step">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="1.7em" height="1.7em" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.9" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M10.29 3.86 1.82 18a2 2 0 0 0 1.71 3h16.94a2 2 0 0 0 1.71-3L13.71 3.86a2 2 0 0 0-3.42 0z"/><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"/><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/></svg>
                <span class="lbl">Step 3</span>
                <strong>Check the Results</strong>
                <span>Same photo on multiple sites = stolen. Exit immediately.</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="ig-foot">92% of scam listings use stolen photos from legitimate breeders' social media accounts</div>
          </figure>

          <div class="verify-steps">
            <div class="verify-step">
              <div class="step-num">1</div>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h3>Right-Click Any Photo in the Listing</h3>
                <p>In Google Chrome or Edge, right-click on any bird photo in the listing. Select <strong>"Search image with Google"</strong> (Chrome) or <strong>"Search for image"</strong> (Edge). This instantly launches a Google Image Search using that exact photo.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="verify-step">
              <div class="step-num">2</div>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h3>If Right-Click Doesn't Work: Save and Upload</h3>
                <p>Save the image to your device, then go to <a href="https://images.google.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">images.google.com</a> → click the camera icon → upload the saved photo. Alternatively use <a href="https://www.tineye.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">TinEye.com</a> — it searches specifically for exact image matches across the web.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="verify-step">
              <div class="step-num">3</div>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h3>Look for the Same Photo on Multiple Sites</h3>
                <p>If the search results show the same bird photo appearing on other websites — different "breeder" pages, stock image sites, unrelated social media accounts, or other pet sales pages — the photo is stolen and the listing is a scam. Also check if the photo appears attributed to a photographer or a different breeder by name.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- ===== SECTION 10: WHOIS CHECK ===== -->
        <a name="whois"></a>
        <div class="section-block" id="whois">
          <h2>How to Check if a Breeder Website Is New (WHOIS Domain Age Check)</h2>

          <p>Scammers build websites fast. A site claiming 10 years of experience might have been created 6 weeks ago. A WHOIS lookup reveals the truth in under 60 seconds.</p>

          <div class="verify-steps">
            <div class="verify-step">
              <div class="step-num">1</div>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h3>Go to lookup.icann.org or whois.domaintools.com</h3>
                <p>Both tools are free. <a href="https://lookup.icann.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">lookup.icann.org</a> is the official ICANN WHOIS registry — the most authoritative source. <a href="https://whois.domaintools.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">whois.domaintools.com</a> shows additional historical data about domain ownership changes.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="verify-step">
              <div class="step-num">2</div>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h3>Enter the Breeder's Domain Name</h3>
                <p>Type the seller's website address (e.g., "exampleafricangreybreeder.com") into the WHOIS search box. Do not include "http://" or "www." — just the domain name and extension.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="verify-step">
              <div class="step-num">3</div>
              <div class="step-content">
                <h3>Find the "Creation Date" — Compare to Experience Claims</h3>
                <p>The "Creation Date" or "Registered On" field shows when the domain was first registered. If a "breeder" claims 15 years of experience but their domain was created 3 months ago, that is a direct contradiction. Legitimate breeders like C.A.Gs have domain registrations spanning multiple years, consistent with their stated experience. Our own domain is happily middle-aged — run the lookup on congoafricangreys.com and check our math.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="warn-box">
            <span class="warn-icon"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="1em" height="1em" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.9" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" style="display:inline-block;vertical-align:-0.125em" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M9 18h6"/><path d="M10 22h4"/><path d="M12 2a7 7 0 0 0-4 12.7c.6.5 1 1.4 1 2.3h6c0-.9.4-1.8 1-2.3A7 7 0 0 0 12 2z"/></svg></span>
            <div class="warn-body">
              <strong>Note on Privacy Protection</strong>
              <p>Many domains use privacy protection services that mask the registrant's personal details. This alone is not a red flag — even legitimate businesses use domain privacy. What matters is the <strong>Creation Date</strong>, which is always visible regardless of privacy protection. If the creation date is recent and the experience claims are old, that's the contradiction to act on.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>


