          <h3>What Health Screening Separates a Real C.A.Gs Bird From a Scam Listing?</h3>

          <div class="snippet-answer">
            <strong>A legitimate C.A.Gs African Grey is verifiable in four documents:</strong> a PCR DNA-sexing certificate, PBFD and Avian Polyomavirus (APV) screening results, a board-certified avian veterinarian's pre-shipment exam, and a hatch certificate matching the closed band on the bird's leg. A scam listing can fake a photo; it cannot fake this paper trail.
          </div>

          <p>Here at C.A.Gs, the screening happens long before a buyer ever sees a listing. Every chick we hand-raise is tested for <strong>PBFD (Psittacine Beak and Feather Disease)</strong> and <strong>Avian Polyomavirus (APV)</strong> — the two viral diseases that scam-sourced and laundered birds most commonly carry, because no one screened the parents and no one quarantined the chicks. We run <strong>PCR-based DNA sexing</strong> on every bird (African Greys cannot be sexed visually — any seller who "can just tell" is guessing or lying), and our <strong>board-certified avian veterinarian</strong> examines each bird before it travels.</p>

          <p>Then the paperwork follows the bird, not the other way around: the <strong>hatch certificate</strong> records the hatch date and the number on the <strong>closed band</strong> placed on the chick's leg in the first weeks of life — a band that physically cannot be slipped onto an adult bird, which is exactly why scammers never mention banding. Our <strong>72-hour written health guarantee</strong> puts our screening on the line in writing, and <a href="/african-grey-parrot-health-guarantee/">our health guarantee page</a> publishes the exact terms. Ask a scammer for any single item on this list and watch the conversation end.</p>

          <h4 class="qa-label">How Do I Verify CongoAfricanGreys.com Is a Real Breeder?</h4>

