        <!-- ===== SECTION 20: HOW TO REPORT ===== -->
        <a name="report-scam"></a>
        <div class="section-block" id="report-scam">
          <h2>How to Report an African Grey Parrot Scam: 5 Agencies That Take Action</h2>

          <p>If you have been defrauded — or if you identify an active scam before losing money — report it immediately. Each agency below handles a different jurisdiction. Filing all five maximizes the chance of a takedown and helps protect the next buyer.</p>

          <h3>Agencies That Take Action</h3>
          <div class="report-steps">

            <div class="report-step">
              <div class="report-step-num">1</div>
              <div class="report-step-body">
                <h4>FBI Internet Crime Complaint Center (IC3)</h4>
                <p>The <a href="https://www.ic3.gov/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">FBI IC3 online fraud portal</a> is the primary federal channel for internet-based fraud. File at ic3.gov. IC3 feeds into federal investigation pools — multiple complaints about the same operator trigger action.</p>
                <h5>What Should Your IC3 Report Include?</h5>
                <h6>Who They Are</h6>
                <p>The seller's name, email address, phone number, and the platform where the listing appeared.</p>
                <h6>How You Paid</h6>
                <p>The payment method used — Zelle, CashApp, wire transfer, or card — plus the account or handle the money went to.</p>
                <h6>What You Lost</h6>
                <p>The total amount, broken into each payment: deposit, shipping crate, insurance, and any "clearance" fees.</p>
                <h6>What You Can Prove</h6>
                <p>All communication records — emails, texts, chat screenshots, and any fake invoices or fabricated documents the scammer sent.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="report-step">
              <div class="report-step-num">2</div>
              <div class="report-step-body">
                <h4>Federal Trade Commission (FTC)</h4>
                <p><a href="https://reportfraud.ftc.gov/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ReportFraud.ftc.gov</a> handles consumer fraud at the federal level. The FTC uses complaint data to identify patterns — a surge of reports about the same phone number or email triggers investigation. Also report to the FTC if the scammer's payment platform (Zelle, CashApp) refuses to cooperate with your refund request.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="report-step">
              <div class="report-step-num">3</div>
              <div class="report-step-body">
                <h4>Your State Attorney General</h4>
                <p>Every state AG office has a consumer protection division. File online at your state's AG website — search "[your state] attorney general consumer complaint." State-level complaints can trigger action against operators based in your state and create public records that warn other buyers. This is especially effective for scammers operating within the same state as the victim.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="report-step">
              <div class="report-step-num">4</div>
              <div class="report-step-body">
                <h4>Your Bank or Credit Card Issuer</h4>
                <p>If you paid by credit card or debit card, call the number on the back of your card immediately and request a chargeback under "item not received" or "fraud."</p>
                <h5>How Fast Do You Need to File the Chargeback?</h5>
                <p>Time is critical — most issuers require the dispute to be filed within 60–120 days of the transaction. If you paid via Zelle through your bank's app, report it as an "unauthorized" transaction; banks have increasingly been reversing Zelle scam payments under regulatory pressure.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="report-step">
              <div class="report-step-num">5</div>
              <div class="report-step-body">
                <h4>The Platform Where the Listing Appeared</h4>
                <p>Report the listing and seller profile to Facebook Marketplace, Craigslist, Hoobly, or whichever platform hosted the scam. Platforms have fraud teams and can remove listings, ban accounts, and in some cases preserve evidence for law enforcement. Use the platform's "Report" button — and also email their trust &amp; safety team directly if the listing is actively targeting other buyers.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

          </div>

          <div class="callout-green">
            <h5>Even If You Can't Get Your Money Back — Report Anyway</h5>
            <p>Many victims don't report because recovery seems unlikely. But the same scammer who took $800 from you is targeting someone else right now. Your report — combined with others — is what puts operators on federal radar. The IC3 and FTC do not act on individual complaints; they act on patterns. Your report is one data point in a pattern that stops the next victim.</p>
          </div>

        </div>

